d, United Kingdom","Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England":"Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1100–1131":"1100–1131","1098–1146":"1098–1146","1114–1180":"1114–1180","1125–1191":"1125–1191","1128–1168":"1128–1168","–1178":"–1178","1131":"1131","1098":"1098","1191":"1191","1180":"1180","1128":"1128","1127":"1127","1114":"1114","1125":"1125","1168":"1168","1146":"1146","1178":"1178","1100":"1100","about 1128":"circa 1128","about 1125":"circa 1125","Raby, Durham, England":"Raby, Durham, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Durham, North Carolina, United States":"Durham, North Carolina, Verenigde Staten van Amerika","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England":"Horncastle, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1100–1131":"1100–1131","1098–1146":"1098–1146","1114–1180":"1114–1180","1125–1191":"1125–1191","1128–1168":"1128–1168","–1178":"–1178","1131":"1131","1098":"1098","1191":"1191","1180":"1180","1128":"1128","1127":"1127","1114":"1114","1125":"1125","1168":"1168","1146":"1146","1178":"1178","1100":"1100","about 1128":"about 1128","about 1125":"about 1125","Raby, Durham, England":"Raby, Durham, England, United Kingdom","Durham, North Carolina, United States":"Durham, North Carolina, United States","England":"England, United Kingdom","Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England":"Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MNU","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Young, Yong, Chong, Hyung, In, Song, Bok, Dae, Hui, Jae, Kwang, Kyong, Kyong Tae, Kyung, Myung, Ae, Cheol, Chul, Chul Ho, Chung, Hak, Hong Suk, Hyung Chul, In Ho.","English: variant of   Munn  .","Korean: there are two Chinese characters for the surname <i>Mun</i>. Although some records indicate that there are as many as 131 Mun clans, only three can be traced. The founding ancestor of the oldest of these, the Namp’yŏng Mun clan, was named Mun Ta-sŏng and was born in 472. According to legend, he was found by Shilla King Chabi Maripkan in a stone box at the end of a rainbow by a lotus pond. The Chinese character Mun was inscribed in the box, so the king gave that as a surname to the child. The founders of the other two Mun clans were originally named   Cha   and   Kim  , but after studying in China they changed their names to Mun (the Chinese character <i>Mun</i> means ‘writing’ or ‘literature’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Munn","meanings":["Scottish (southwestern): variant of   McMunn  .","English: from Middle English <i>Munne</i>, representing an Old Norse male personal name, <i>Munni</i> or <i>Munnr</i>, originally a nickname from Old Norse <i>munnr</i> ‘mouth’.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>mun</i> ‘mouth’ (Old Norse <i>munnr</i>)."]}]},{"name":"married","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Arnell, Hjalmer.","German: habitational name from a place called Harried in Bavaria."],"variants":[]},{"name":"NEVILLE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"FNU","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Wealthy’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"FNU MNU married NEVILLE was born in 1100, in Raby, Durham, England, United Kingdom. She married GEOFFREY I de NEVILLE , Baron Neville of Horncastle, Circuit Justice of Yorkshire in 1127, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 dau